# File layout

SOLID and Clean Code applied to the file system itself. Pair this with [code-style.mdc](code-style.mdc) and [naming.mdc](naming.mdc).

## The rule

**Exactly one function per `.ts` file.** The file's single purpose is to implement that one function. The filename is the kebab-case form of the function name.

```text
parseAreaData         → src/game/parse-area-data.ts        (export function parseAreaData)
findEmptyEnemySlot    → src/game/find-empty-enemy-slot.ts  (export function findEmptyEnemySlot)
tickPlayer            → src/game/tick-player.ts            (export function tickPlayer)
```

## Every helper goes to `utils/` — no exceptions

A "helper" is any function called by the file's main function. **Reuse count is irrelevant.** A one-callsite private helper called only by `parseAreaData` lives in its own file under `utils/`, not inside `parse-area-data.ts`.

We are deliberately not optimising for reusability. We are optimising for **scannability** and **single-responsibility at the file-system level**. If you want to know what `parseAreaData` calls, you read its imports.

## Why

- Any function in the repo is locatable by its filename — no grep needed.
- One concern per file means a file diff tells one story.
- The structure happens to mirror the disassembly's labelled-subroutine table 1:1 (per [docs/adr/0003-modern-naming-structural-fidelity.md](../../docs/adr/0003-modern-naming-structural-fidelity.md)), so structural fidelity falls out for free.

## Where helpers live

Each domain has its own `utils/` folder:

- `src/engine/utils/` — engine helpers.
- `src/game/utils/` — game helpers.
- `src/game/enemies/utils/` — sub-domain helpers when the sub-domain grows them.
- `src/utils/` — genuinely cross-domain helpers. If you reach there often, the helper probably wants its own domain.

The same one-function-per-file rule applies recursively inside `utils/`.

## What may stay in the file alongside the one function

- **Local `const`s** scoped to the function — configuration of the function itself (e.g. `const MAX_JUMP_FRAMES = 30` inside `tick-player-jump.ts`). These are not "helpers".
- **Local `interface` / `type`** declarations describing the function's parameters or return shape (per [code-style.mdc](code-style.mdc)'s interface-first rule).
- **The single `export function`** itself.
- That is all.

## Carve-outs for non-functions

The "one function" rule applies to *functions*. Files that contain no functions can group related declarations:

- **Data files** (`src/data/levels.ts`, `palettes.ts`, `metatiles.ts`, ...) — related `Uint8Array` / readonly-tuple constants.
- **Constants files** (`src/data/constants.ts`) — related constant values.
- **Type-only files** (`types.ts` at a domain root) — `interface` / `type` declarations shared by ≥ 2 files in that domain.
- **Module barrels** (`index.ts`) — only when an outside caller benefits from a deliberate public surface; never a dump of every file in the folder.

## Tests

`__tests__/<source-name>.test.ts` mirrors the file under test. One test file per source file.
